INSERT INTO `information_sheets` (`id`, `module_id`, `sheet_number`, `title`, `description`, `content`, `file_path`, `original_filename`, `order`, `is_active`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`) VALUES (3,3,'1.2','Electronic Components','Resistors, Color Coding, Conversion, Tolerance, Circuits and Ohm\'s Law','<h2>INFORMATION SHEET No. 1.2</h2>\n<p><em>Resistors, Color coding, Conversion, Tolerance, Circuits and Ohm\'s Law</em></p>\n\n<h3>Electronic Components</h3>\n<h4>DEVICES: RESISTORS</h4>\n\n<p>A <strong>resistor</strong> is an electronic device that limits or opposes the amount of current in a circuit. A resistor has two terminals across which electricity must pass, and is designed to drop the voltage of the current as it flows from one terminal to the next. A resistor is primarily used to create and maintain a known safe current within an electrical component.</p>\n\n<p>Every resistor falls into one of two categories: <strong>fixed</strong> or <strong>variable</strong>.</p>\n\n<h4>1. Fixed Resistor</h4>\n<p>Has a predetermined amount of resistance to current.</p>\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/IMG_20251016_190948.jpg\" alt=\"Fixed Resistors\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>2. Variable Resistor</h4>\n<p>Can be adjusted to give different levels of resistance. Examples are the carbon composition and wirewound resistors. Variable resistors are also called <strong>potentiometers</strong> and are commonly used as volume controls on audio devices.</p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<h3>Resistor Color Coding</h3>\n<p>The color code chart is applicable to most of the common four-band and five-band resistors. Five-band resistors are usually precision resistors with tolerances of 1% and 2%. Most of the four-band resistors have tolerances of 5%, 10% and 20%.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/IMG_20251016_190957.jpg\" alt=\"Resistor Color Coding\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<p>The color codes of a resistor are read from left to right, with the tolerance band oriented to the right side. Match the color of the first band to its associated number under the digit column in the color chart. This is the first digit of the resistance value. Match the second band to its associated color under the digit column in the chart to get the second digit of the resistance value.</p>\n\n<p>Match the color band preceding the tolerance band (last band) to its associated number under the multiplier column on the chart. This number is the multiplier for the quantity previously indicated by the first two digits (four-band resistor) or the first three digits (five-band resistor) and is used to determine the total marked value of the resistor in ohms (see Ohm\'s Law, below).</p>\n\n<h4>Tolerance</h4>\n<p>Is the maximum and minimum accepted value of resistor when measuring it. This multiplier, by multiplying the percentage of the fourth or fifth colored value of the resistor on the first and second color, then after is adding and subtracting, adding it on the value of the resistor first and second color will get the maximum accepted value of the resistor and subtracting it will get the minimum.</p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<h3>How to Test the Resistor Using Multi-tester</h3>\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/IMG_20251016_191004.jpg\" alt=\"Testing Resistor with Multi-tester\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<hr>\n\n<h3>OHM\'S Law</h3>\n<p>Ohm\'s Law states that an electrical circuit\'s current is directly proportional to its voltage, and inversely proportional to its resistance. So, if voltage increases, for example, the current will also increase, and if resistance increases, current decreases; both situations directly influence the efficiency of electrical circuits. To understand Ohm\'s Law, it\'s important to understand the concepts of current, voltage, and resistance: current is the flow of an electric charge, voltage is the force that drives the current in one direction, and resistance is the opposition of an object to having current pass through it.</p>\n\n<p>The formula for Ohm\'s Law is:</p>\n<p style=\"font-size: 1.2em; text-align: center;\">\n<strong>I = V/R &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; V = I × R &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R = V/I</strong>\n</p>\n<p>where:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>V</strong> = voltage in volts</li>\n<li><strong>I</strong> = current in amperes</li>\n<li><strong>R</strong> = resistance in ohms</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This formula can be used to analyze the voltage, current, and resistance of electricity circuits. Depending on what you are trying to solve we can rearrange it two other ways.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/IMG_20251016_191011.jpg\" alt=\"Ohm\'s Law Explanation\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<hr>\n\n<h3>ELECTRICAL CIRCUITS</h3>\n<p>An <strong>electrical circuit</strong> is a device that uses electricity to perform a task, such as run a vacuum or power a lamp. The circuit is a closed loop formed by a power source, wires, a fuse, a load, and a switch. Electricity flows through the circuit and is delivered to the object it is powering, such as the vacuum motor or light bulb, after which the electricity is sent back to the original source; this return of electricity enables the circuit to keep the electricity current flowing.</p>\n\n<h4>Types of Circuits</h4>\n\n<p>A <strong>Series Circuit</strong> is the simplest because it has only one possible path that the electrical current may flow; if the electrical circuit is broken, none of the load devices will work.</p>\n\n<p>In the <strong>Parallel Circuit</strong>, the electricity can travel to two or more paths. The path in which the electricity travels are separate and if ever one of its path fails to function, the electricity can still flow back to the source through the other paths.</p>\n\n<p>A <strong>Series-Parallel Circuit</strong>, however, is a combination of the first two: it attaches some of the loads to a series circuit and others to parallel circuits.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/IMG_20251016_191020.jpg\" alt=\"Types of Circuits\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>Series Circuit Formula:</h4>\n<p style=\"font-size: 1.1em;\"><strong>R<sub>total</sub> = R<sub>1</sub> + R<sub>2</sub> + R<sub>3</sub></strong></p>\n\n<h4>Parallel Circuit Formula:</h4>\n<p style=\"font-size: 1.1em;\"><strong>R<sub>total</sub> = 1 / (1/R<sub>1</sub> + 1/R<sub>2</sub> + 1/R<sub>3</sub>)</strong></p>\n\n<h4>Formula for 2 Parallel Circuit only:</h4>\n<p style=\"font-size: 1.1em;\"><strong>R<sub>T</sub> = (R1 × R2) / (R1 + R2)</strong></p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/IMG_20251016_191036.jpg\" alt=\"Circuit Calculations\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<hr>\n<p><em>Prepare for a Self-check and Task Sheet, please provide a sheet of paper as answer sheet.</em></p>',NULL,NULL,2,1,'2026-03-26 19:38:28','2026-03-31 06:26:41',NULL),(4,3,'1.3','Capacitors and Diodes',NULL,'<h2>INFORMATION SHEET No. 1.3</h2>\n<p><em>Capacitors and Diodes</em></p>\n\n<p>This information sheet covers two important electronic components: <strong>Capacitors</strong> and <strong>Diodes</strong>. Understanding these components is essential for working with electronic circuits.</p>\n\n<p>Navigate through the topics below to learn about each component in detail.</p>',NULL,NULL,0,1,'2026-03-31 18:07:17','2026-03-31 18:07:17',NULL),(5,3,'1.4','Transistors, Integrated Circuits and Transformers',NULL,'<h2>INFORMATION SHEET No. 1.4</h2>\n<p><em>Transistors, Integrated Circuit\'s (IC\'s) and Transformers</em></p>\n\n<p>This information sheet covers three important electronic components used in modern circuits. Navigate through the topics below to learn about each component.</p>',NULL,NULL,0,1,'2026-03-31 18:11:19','2026-03-31 18:11:19',NULL),(6,3,'1.5','Schematic Diagram, Pictorial Diagram, Block Diagram and PCB Making',NULL,'<h2>INFORMATION SHEET No. 1.5</h2>\n<p><em>Schematic Diagram, Pictorial Diagram, Block Diagram and PCB Making</em></p>\n\n<p>This information sheet covers the different types of electronic diagrams and the process of making printed circuit boards (PCB).</p>',NULL,NULL,0,1,'2026-03-31 19:40:11','2026-03-31 19:40:11',NULL),(7,3,'1.6','Soldering and De-soldering, Terminalizing and Connecting, Troubleshooting Process',NULL,'<h2>INFORMATION SHEET No. 1.6</h2>\n<p><em>Soldering and De-soldering, Terminalizing and Connecting, Troubleshooting Process</em></p>\n\n<p>This information sheet covers the essential skills of soldering, de-soldering, and troubleshooting electronic circuits.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.6/IMG_20251025_214550.jpg\" alt=\"Soldering Process Overview\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">',NULL,NULL,0,1,'2026-03-31 19:49:59','2026-03-31 19:49:59',NULL);
