INSERT INTO `topics` (`id`, `information_sheet_id`, `title`, `topic_number`, `content`, `parts`, `file_path`, `original_filename`, `document_content`, `order`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`) VALUES (1,3,'DEVICES: RESISTORS','1.2.1','<h3>Electronic Components</h3>\n<p>A <strong>resistor</strong> is an electronic device that limits or opposes the amount of current in a circuit. A resistor has two terminals across which electricity must pass, and is designed to drop the voltage of the current as it flows from one terminal to the next. A resistor is primarily used to create and maintain a known safe current within an electrical component.</p>\n\n<p>Every resistor falls into one of two categories: fixed or variable.</p>\n\n<h4>1. Fixed Resistor</h4>\n<p>Has a predetermined amount of resistance to current.</p>\n\n\n<h4>2. Variable Resistor</h4>\n<p>Can be adjusted to give different levels of resistance. Examples are the carbon composition and wirewound resistors. Variable resistors are also called potentiometers and are commonly used as volume controls on audio devices.</p>\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2026-03-26 19:39:03','2026-03-26 20:40:48',NULL),(2,3,'Resistor Color Coding','1.2.2','<h3>Resistor Color Coding</h3>\n<p>The color code chart is applicable to most of the common four-band and five-band resistors. Five-band resistors are usually precision resistors with tolerances of 1% and 2%. Most of the four-band resistors have tolerances of 5%, 10% and 20%.</p>\n\n<h4>Reading the Color Code</h4>\n<p>The color codes of a resistor are read from left to right, with the tolerance band oriented to the right side. Match the color of the first band to its associated number under the digit column in the color chart. This is the first digit of the resistance value. Match the second band to its associated color under the digit column in the color chart to get the second digit of the resistance value.</p>\n\n<h4>Resistor - 4 Bands</h4>\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\">\n<tr><th>Color</th><th>Digit</th><th>Multiplier</th><th>Tolerance</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Black</td><td>0</td><td>1</td><td>-</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Brown</td><td>1</td><td>10</td><td>±1%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Red</td><td>2</td><td>100</td><td>±2%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Orange</td><td>3</td><td>1,000</td><td>-</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Yellow</td><td>4</td><td>10,000</td><td>-</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Green</td><td>5</td><td>100,000</td><td>±0.5%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Blue</td><td>6</td><td>1,000,000</td><td>±0.25%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Violet</td><td>7</td><td>10,000,000</td><td>±0.1%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Grey</td><td>8</td><td>100,000,000</td><td>±0.05%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>White</td><td>9</td><td>-</td><td>-</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Gold</td><td>-</td><td>0.1</td><td>±5%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Silver</td><td>-</td><td>0.01</td><td>±10%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>None</td><td>-</td><td>-</td><td>±20%</td></tr>\n</table>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,2,'2026-03-26 19:39:16','2026-03-26 19:39:16',NULL),(3,3,'Tolerance','1.2.3','<h3>Tolerance</h3>\n<p>Tolerance is the maximum and minimum accepted value of resistor when measuring it. This is computed by multiplying the percentage of the fourth or fifth colored value of the resistor on the first and second color, then after it adding and subtracting, adding it on the value of the resistor first and second color will get the maximum accepted value of the resistor and subtracting it will get the minimum.</p>\n\n<h4>Sample Computation (5% Tolerance)</h4>\n<p><strong>Brown, Black, Red, Gold:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>1000 = resistor value</li>\n<li>× 0.05 = resistor 5% value</li>\n<li>= 50</li>\n<li>1000 + 50 = 1050 maximum tolerance</li>\n<li>1000 - 50 = 950 minimum tolerance</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Sample Computation (10% Tolerance)</h4>\n<p><strong>Brown, Black, Red, Silver:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>1000 = resistor value</li>\n<li>× 0.1 = resistor 10% tolerance</li>\n<li>= 100</li>\n<li>1000 + 100 = 1100 maximum tolerance</li>\n<li>1000 - 100 = 900 minimum tolerance</li>\n</ul>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,3,'2026-03-26 19:39:28','2026-03-26 19:39:28',NULL),(4,3,'How to Test the Resistor using Multi-tester','1.2.4','<h3>How to Test the Resistor using Multi-tester</h3>\n<p>To test a resistor, you need to use a multi-meter (also called a multi-tester) set to the resistance (ohms) measurement mode.</p>\n\n<h4>Steps:</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Decode the color code value of the resistor</li>\n<li>Compute the minimum and maximum tolerance</li>\n<li>Using the suggested ohm\'s range, check using the multi-meter</li>\n<li>Write down the parts, description (R1, R2, etc.), actual reading (resistance), the range and the remarks if good or defective</li>\n<li>Submit to Trainer for checking</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h4>Reading Examples:</h4>\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\">\n<tr><th>Resistor</th><th>Range</th><th>Resistance</th><th>Coded Value</th><th>Multiplier</th><th>Tolerance</th></tr>\n<tr><td>R1</td><td>Rx1</td><td>4Ω</td><td>4</td><td>1</td><td>-</td></tr>\n<tr><td>R2</td><td>Rx10</td><td>100Ω</td><td>10</td><td>10</td><td>-</td></tr>\n<tr><td>R3</td><td>Rx100</td><td>1.4kΩ</td><td>14</td><td>100</td><td>-</td></tr>\n<tr><td>R4</td><td>Rx1k</td><td>10kΩ</td><td>10</td><td>1k</td><td>-</td></tr>\n</table>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,4,'2026-03-26 19:39:40','2026-03-26 19:39:40',NULL),(5,3,'Ohm\'s Law','1.2.5','<h3>Ohm\'s Law</h3>\n<p>Ohm\'s Law states that an electrical circuit\'s current is directly proportional to its voltage, and inversely proportional to its resistance. So, if voltage increases, for example, the current will also increase, and if resistance increases, current decreases; both situations directly influence the efficiency of electrical circuits.</p>\n\n<p>To understand Ohm\'s Law, it\'s important to understand the concepts of current, voltage, and resistance:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Current</strong> is the flow of electric charge</li>\n<li><strong>Voltage</strong> is the force that drives the current in one direction</li>\n<li><strong>Resistance</strong> is the opposition of an object to having current pass through it</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>The Formulas for Ohm\'s Law:</h4>\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"10\">\n<tr>\n<td><strong>I = V/R</strong></td>\n<td><strong>V = I × R</strong></td>\n<td><strong>R = V/I</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n\n<p>Where:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>V</strong> = voltage in volts</li>\n<li><strong>I</strong> = current in amperes</li>\n<li><strong>R</strong> = resistance in ohms</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<p>Voltage = 100 volts<br>\nResistance = 100 ohms(Ω)<br>\nCurrent = ?</p>\n<p><strong>Answer:</strong> I = V/R = 100/100 = 1 ampere</p>\n<p><em>(The symbol for an Ohm looks like a horseshoe and is pictured after the \"100\" in the diagram above.)</em></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,5,'2026-03-26 19:40:57','2026-03-26 19:40:57',NULL),(6,3,'Electrical Circuits','1.2.6','<h3>ELECTRICAL CIRCUITS</h3>\n<p>An <strong>electrical circuit</strong> is a device that uses electricity to perform a task, such as run a vacuum or power a lamp. The circuit is a closed loop formed by a power source, wires, a fuse, a load, and a switch. Electricity flows through the circuit and is delivered to the object it is powering, such as the vacuum motor or light bulb, after which the electricity is sent back to the original source; this return of electricity enables the circuit to keep the electricity current flowing.</p>\n\n<h3>Types of Circuits</h3>\n\n<h4>1. Series Circuit</h4>\n<p>A Series Circuit is the simplest because it has only one possible path that the electrical current may flow. If the electrical circuit is broken, none of the load devices will work.</p>\n<p><strong>Series Circuit Formula:</strong> R<sub>total</sub> = R₁ + R₂ + R₃</p>\n\n<h4>2. Parallel Circuit</h4>\n<p>In the Parallel Circuit, the electricity can travel to two or more paths. The path in which the electricity travels are separate and if even one of its path fails to function, the electricity can still flow back to the source through the other paths.</p>\n<p><strong>Parallel Circuit Formula:</strong></p>\n<p>R<sub>total</sub> = 1 / (1/R₁ + 1/R₂ + 1/R₃)</p>\n<p><strong>Formula for 2 Parallel Circuit only:</strong></p>\n<p>R<sub>t</sub> = (R1 × R2) / (R1 + R2)</p>\n\n<h4>3. Series-Parallel Circuit</h4>\n<p>A Series-Parallel Circuit, however, is a combination of the first two. It attaches some of the loads to a series circuit and others to parallel circuits.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,6,'2026-03-26 19:41:12','2026-03-26 19:41:12',NULL),(7,4,'Capacitors','1','<h3>DEVICES: CAPACITORS</h3>\n\n<p>A <strong>capacitor</strong> is an electronic device or components that store or accumulate electrical energy in a circuit. A capacitor is a tool consisting of two conductive plates, each of which hosts an opposite charge. These plates are separated by a dielectric or other form of insulator, which helps them maintain an electric charge.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.3/IMG_20251016_233302.jpg\" alt=\"Capacitors Overview\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<p><em>Farad</em> – is the measured unit of a capacitance, the higher the farad, the longer it holds the stored charges; the lower the farad, the shorter it holds the stored charges.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Capacitance</strong> is the quantity of electrical energy that a capacitor can store. Capacitance is dependent upon:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Thickness of dielectric</li>\n<li>Area of the plates</li>\n<li>Constant of dielectric</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Capacitor Functions</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Coupling</strong> – to prevent DC from entering the circuit.</li>\n<li><strong>De-coupling</strong> – to prevent or protect the circuit from another circuit.</li>\n<li><strong>Noisefilters or Snubbers</strong> – to protect the circuit from distortion and interference.</li>\n<li><strong>Motorstarter</strong> – is used for starting the motor.</li>\n<li><strong>Tuned-inCircuit</strong> – is used for tuning circuit.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Types of Capacitors</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Polystyrene (Film capacitor)</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Mylar</strong> (for high voltage charge)</li>\n<li><strong>Polyethylene (Film capacitor)</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Mica</strong> (for high voltage charge)</li>\n<li><strong>Tantalum</strong> (electrolytic type)</li>\n<li><strong>Ceramic</strong> (for small amount of charge)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.3/IMG_20251016_233329.jpg\" alt=\"Types of Capacitors\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>Electrolytic Capacitors</h4>\n<p>Electrolytic capacitors have several prominent characteristics, including:</p>\n<ol type=\"a\">\n<li>High capacitance-to-size ratio;</li>\n<li>Polarity sensitivity and terminals marked + and -;</li>\n<li>Allow more leakage current than other types; and</li>\n<li>Have their C value and voltage rating printed on them.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>The main advantage of the electrolytic capacitor is the large capacitance-per-size factor. Two obvious disadvantages are the polarity, which must be observed, and the higher leakage current feature.</p>\n\n<h4>Variable Capacitor</h4>\n<p>A variable capacitor is a special type of capacitor, most commonly used for tuning radios, which allows the amount of electrical charge it can hold to be altered over a certain range, measured in a unit known as farads. Regular capacitors build up and store an electrical charge until it is ready to use. While a variable capacitor stores the charge in the same fashion, it can be adjusted as many times as desired to store different amounts of electricity.</p>\n\n<p>Two types of variable capacitors include air variable capacitors and vacuum variable capacitors.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.3/IMG_20251016_233400.jpg\" alt=\"Variable Capacitors and Testing\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>How to Test the Capacitor Using Multi-tester</h4>\n<p>Testing capacitors involves checking for:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Good Capacitor</strong> - Shows proper capacitance reading</li>\n<li><strong>Shorted Capacitor</strong> - Shows continuity/low resistance</li>\n<li><strong>Open Capacitor</strong> - Shows no reading/infinite resistance</li>\n<li><strong>Leaky Capacitor</strong> - Shows some resistance but not proper capacitance</li>\n</ul>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.3/IMG_20251016_233418.jpg\" alt=\"Testing Capacitors\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2026-03-31 18:07:17','2026-03-31 18:07:17',NULL),(8,4,'Diodes','2','<h3>DEVICES: DIODE</h3>\n\n<p>A <strong>diode</strong> is a semi-conductor device that permits the flow of current in only one direction. A Diode can convert electric current from AC to DC or from Alternating Current to Direct Current. This is called Rectification, and rectifier diodes are most commonly used in low current power supplies.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Rectification</strong> is a process of converting AC to DC.</p>\n\n<h4>Diode Parts</h4>\n<p>A diode has 2 parts:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Anode (A)</strong> +</li>\n<li><strong>Cathode (K)</strong> -</li>\n</ul>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.3/IMG_20251016_233418.jpg\" alt=\"Diode Basics\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>TYPES OF DIODE</h4>\n\n<h5>1. Rectifier Diode</h5>\n<p>Converts AC to DC.</p>\n\n<h5>2. Signal Diode</h5>\n<p>Both diodes work the same way by allowing current to flow in one direction. The differences have to do with power and frequency characteristics. They are made from a p-n junction and are two lead devices.</p>\n<p>Small signal diodes have much lower power and current ratings, around 150mA, 500mW maximum compared to rectifier diodes, they can also function better in high frequency applications or in clipping and switching applications with short-duration pulse waveforms.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Converts Intermediate Frequency (IF) to Audio Frequency (AF).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h5>3. Regulator Diode</h5>\n<p>Used for voltage regulation.</p>\n\n<h5>4. Temperature Dependent Diode</h5>\n<p>Used for temperatures hot or cold to automatically on and off.</p>\n\n<h5>5. Light Emitting Diode (L.E.D)</h5>\n<p>Is a semiconductor light source. LEDs are used as indicator lamps in many devices and are increasingly used for other lighting. Photodiode or Photo Sensitive Diode - Allows current flow when exposed to light (vice versa).</p>\n\n<h5>6. Photodiode (Photosensitive diode)</h5>\n<p>Is a type of photodetector capable of converting light into either current or voltage, depending upon the mode of operation. The common, traditional solar cell used to generate electric solar power is a large-area photodiode.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.3/IMG_20251016_233502.jpg\" alt=\"Types of Diodes\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>How to Test the Diode Using Multi-tester</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Good Diode</strong> - Forward bias shows low resistance, reverse bias shows high/infinite resistance</li>\n<li><strong>Shorted Diode</strong> - Shows low resistance in both directions</li>\n<li><strong>Open Diode</strong> - Shows high/infinite resistance in both directions</li>\n<li><strong>Leaky Diode</strong> - Shows some resistance in both directions</li>\n</ul>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.3/IMG_20251016_233517.jpg\" alt=\"Testing Diodes\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,2,'2026-03-31 18:07:37','2026-03-31 18:07:37',NULL),(9,5,'Transistors','1','<h3>DEVICES: TRANSISTOR</h3>\n\n<p>It is an electronic semi-device which provides oscillation, amplification, switching and rectification of electrical current. The principal materials used are germanium and silicon. Basically, there are two kinds of transistors, namely:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Positive Negative Positive (PNP)</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Negative Positive Negative (NPN)</strong></li>\n</ol>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.4/IMG_20251016_234054.jpg\" alt=\"Transistor Overview\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<p><strong>Oscillation</strong> - A process of moving back and forth, to and from.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplification</strong> - A process of converting.</p>\n\n<p>A transistor is an electronic amplifying device with 2 junction type. Transistors are the NPN and PNP impurity materials utilized to determine the conductivity type of a semi-conductor.</p>\n\n<p>A PNP transistor is made by sandwiching a slab of silicon with \"N-type\" impurities between the 2 layers of silicon with \"P-type\" semi-conductor material. Silicon is generally used for NPN bipolar with N-type semi-conductor materials because of its lower internal voltage drop. Germanium is used for some power type transistor.</p>\n\n<h4>Transistor Parts</h4>\n<p>Transistors are composed of three parts – a base, a collector, and an emitter. The base is the gate controller device for the larger electrical supply. The collector is the larger electrical supply, and the emitter is the outlet for that supply.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>B</strong> – Base – Input</li>\n<li><strong>C</strong> – Collector – output</li>\n<li><strong>E</strong> – Emitter – Ground</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Silicon Controlled Rectifier (SCR)</h4>\n<p>A silicon-controlled rectifier (or semiconductor-controlled rectifier) is a four-layer solid state current controlling device. The name \"silicon controlled rectifier\" or SCR is General Electric\'s trade name for a type of thyristor.</p>\n\n<p>SCRs are unidirectional devices (i.e. can conduct current only in one direction) as opposed to TRIACs which are bidirectional (i.e. current can flow through them in either direction). SCRs can be triggered normally only by currents going into the gate as opposed to TRIACs which can be triggered normally by either a positive or a negative current applied to its gate electrode.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.4/IMG_20251016_234115.jpg\" alt=\"Integrated Circuits\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2026-03-31 18:11:19','2026-03-31 18:11:19',NULL),(10,5,'Integrated Circuits (ICs)','2','<h3>DEVICES: INTEGRATED CIRCUIT (IC)</h3>\n\n<p><strong>Integrated Circuits (ICs)</strong> are used in all types of modern electronic devices. They are integrated, meaning that they are made as a total circuit and housed in one enclosure. The enclosure may take a number of shapes, it may be similar to a 2-5 transistor package with 8 leads instead of 3, it may be what is referred to as a dual in-line package (DIP) with as many as 24 leads. All components are manufactured as a common unit.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.4/IMG_20251016_234234.jpg\" alt=\"Types of ICs\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>Two Major Kinds of ICs:</h4>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Analog (or linear)</strong> which are used as amplifiers, timers and oscillators</li>\n<li><strong>Digital (or logic)</strong> which is used in microprocessors and memories</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>Some ICs are combinations of both analog and digital.</p>\n\n<h4>Three Categories of IC Packages:</h4>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Small scale integration (SSI)</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Medium scale Integration (MSI)</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Large scale integration</strong></li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>The SSI package generally has fewer than 200 components in it, MSI and LSI packages may have anywhere from 1000 to 256,000 or more components.</p>\n\n<h4>Types of IC Packages:</h4>\n\n<p><strong>Dual In-line Package (DIP) IC</strong> – This is an electronic device package with a rectangular housing and two parallel rows of electrical connecting pins. The package may be through-hole mounted to a printed circuit board or inserted in a socket.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Linear IC</strong> – This is a solid-state analog device characterized by a theoretically infinite number of possible operating states. It operates over a continuous range of input levels. In contrast, a digital IC has a finite number of discrete input and output states.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Ball Grid Array (BGA) IC</strong> – This is a type of surface-mount packaging used for integrated circuits. Ball-grid array (BGA) packages are used to permanently mount devices such as microprocessors.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Surface-Mounted Device (SMD) IC</strong> – This is a method for constructing electronic circuits in which the components are mounted directly onto the surface of printed circuit boards (PCBs). An electronic device so made is called a surface-mount device (SMD).</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.4/IMG_20251016_234249.jpg\" alt=\"Transformers and Power Supply\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,2,'2026-03-31 18:11:38','2026-03-31 18:11:38',NULL),(11,5,'Transformers & Power Supply','3','<h3>DEVICES: TRANSFORMERS & POWER SUPPLY</h3>\n\n<h4>Types of Power Supply</h4>\n<p>There are many types of power supply. Most are designed to convert high voltage AC mains electricity to a suitable low voltage supply for electronic circuits and other devices. A power supply can be broken down into a series of blocks, each of which performs a particular function.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.4/IMG_20251016_234249.jpg\" alt=\"Power Supply Block Diagram\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>Block Diagram of a Regulated Power Supply System:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Transformer</strong> - steps down high voltage AC mains to low voltage AC.</li>\n<li><strong>Rectifier</strong> - converts AC to DC, but the DC output is varying.</li>\n<li><strong>Smoothing</strong> - smooths the DC from varying greatly to a small ripple.</li>\n<li><strong>Regulator</strong> - eliminates ripple by setting DC output to a fixed voltage.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Power Supply Configurations:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Transformer only</li>\n<li>Transformer + Rectifier</li>\n<li>Transformer + Rectifier + Smoothing</li>\n<li>Transformer + Rectifier + Smoothing + Regulator</li>\n</ul>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.4/IMG_20251016_234256.jpg\" alt=\"Power Supply Types\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>Transformer</h4>\n<p>Transformers convert AC electricity from one voltage to another with little loss of power. Transformers work only with AC and this is one of the reasons why mains electricity is AC.</p>\n\n<p>Step-up transformers increase voltage, step-down transformers reduce voltage. Most power supplies use a step-down transformer to reduce the dangerously high mains voltage (220V) to a safer low voltage.</p>\n\n<h4>Parts of Transformer</h4>\n<p>The input coil is called the <strong>primary</strong> and the output coil is called the <strong>secondary</strong>. There is no electrical connection between the two coils, instead they are linked by an alternating magnetic field created in the soft iron core of the transformer. The two lines in the middle of the circuit symbol represent the core.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.4/IMG_20251016_234309.jpg\" alt=\"Transformer Parts\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<p>Transformers waste very little power so the power out is (almost) equal to the power in. Note that as voltage is stepped down current is stepped up.</p>\n\n<p>The ratio of the number of turns on each coil, called the turn\'s ratio, determines the ratio of the voltages. A step-down transformer has a large number of turns on its primary (input) coil which is connected to the high voltage mains supply, and a small number of turns on its secondary (output) coil to give a low output voltage.</p>\n\n<h4>Kinds of Transformer:</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Power Transformer</li>\n<li>Isolation Transformer</li>\n<li>Auto Transformer</li>\n<li>Audio Transformer</li>\n<li>RF and IF Transformer</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h4>Types of Power Transformer:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Center Tap Transformer</li>\n<li>Multi Tap Transformer</li>\n</ul>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,3,'2026-03-31 18:11:58','2026-03-31 18:11:58',NULL),(12,5,'Rectifiers & Smoothing','4','<h3>Rectifier</h3>\n<p>There are several ways of connecting diodes to make a rectifier to convert AC to DC. The bridge rectifier is the most important and it produces full-wave varying DC. A full-wave rectifier can also be made from just two diodes if a center-tapped transformer is used. This method is rarely used in practice.</p>\n\n<h4>Bridge Rectifier</h4>\n<p>A bridge rectifier can be made using four individual diodes, but it is also available in special packages containing the four diodes required. It is called a full-wave rectifier because it uses all the AC wave (both positive and negative sections). 1.4V is used up in the bridge rectifier because each diode uses 0.7V when conducting and there are always two diodes conducting, as shown in the diagram below.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.4/IMG_20251016_234318.jpg\" alt=\"Bridge Rectifier\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<p>Bridge rectifiers are rated by the maximum current they can pass and the maximum reverse voltage they can withstand (this must be at least three times the supply RMS voltage so the rectifier can withstand the peak voltages).</p>\n\n<h4>Single Diode Rectifier</h4>\n<p>A single diode can be used as a rectifier but this produces half-wave varying DC which has gaps when the AC is negative. It is hard to smooth this sufficiently well to supply electronic circuits unless they require a very small current so smoothing capacitor does not significantly discharge during the gaps.</p>\n\n<h4>Smoothing</h4>\n<p>Smoothing is performed by a large value <strong>electrolytic capacitor</strong> connected across the DC supply to act as a reservoir, supplying current to the output when the varying DC voltage from the rectifier is falling. The diagram shows the unsmoothed varying DC (dotted line) and the smoothed DC (solid line).</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.4/IMG_20251016_234326.jpg\" alt=\"Smoothing\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<p>The capacitor charges quickly near the peak of the varying DC, and then discharges as it supplies current to the output.</p>\n\n<h4>Regulator</h4>\n<p>Voltage regulator ICs are available with fixed (typically 5, 12 and 15V) or variable output voltages. They are also rated by the maximum current they can pass. Negative voltage regulators are available, mainly for use in dual supplies. Most regulators include some automatic protection from excessive current (overload protection) and overheating (thermal protection).</p>\n\n<p>Many of the fixed voltage regulator ICs have 3 leads and look like power transistors, such as the 7805 +5V 1A regulator shown on the right. They include a hole for attaching a heatsink if necessary.</p>\n\n<p><em>Prepare for a Self check and Task Sheet, please provide a sheet of paper as answer sheet.</em></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,4,'2026-03-31 18:12:22','2026-03-31 18:12:22',NULL),(13,6,'Schematic Diagram','1','<h3>SCHEMATIC DIAGRAM</h3>\n\n<p>A drawing showing all significant components, parts, or tasks (and their interconnections) of a circuit, device, flow, process, or project by means of standard symbols.</p>\n\n<p>A connection of Resistors in series and parallel is also a schematic diagram, below is a sample of complicated diagrams where capacitors, and diodes are added in series – parallel connections.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.5/IMG_20251025_214115.jpg\" alt=\"Sample Schematic Diagram\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2026-03-31 19:40:11','2026-03-31 19:40:11',NULL),(14,6,'Pictorial Diagram','2','<h3>PICTORIAL DIAGRAM</h3>\n\n<p>A simplified diagram which shows the various components of a system (motorcycle, car, ship, electronic devices, airplane, etc) without regard to their physical location, how the wiring is marked, or how the wiring is routed. It does, however, show you the sequence in which the components are connected.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.5/IMG_20251025_214128.jpg\" alt=\"Pictorial Diagram Example\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>Sample of Pictorial and Schematic Symbols</h4>\n<table border=\"1\" style=\"width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;\">\n<tr><th>Component Type</th><th>Pictorial Representation</th><th>Schematic Symbol</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Conductors (connected)</td><td>Wire junction</td><td>Dot at intersection</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Conductors (not connected)</td><td>Wires crossing</td><td>Arc/bridge at crossing</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Cell</td><td>Battery cell</td><td>Long and short lines</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Battery</td><td>Battery pack</td><td>Multiple cell symbols</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Switch (SPST)</td><td>Toggle switch</td><td>Open/close contact</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h4>Additional Schematic and Pictorial Symbols</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Capacitor-Non Polarized</li>\n<li>Capacitor-Polarized</li>\n<li>Resistor</li>\n<li>Variable Resistor</li>\n<li>Diode</li>\n<li>Light Emitting Diode (LED)</li>\n<li>Symbols for Ground</li>\n</ul>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.5/IMG_20251025_214152.jpg\" alt=\"Schematic Symbols\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>Schematic Diagram of Flip-Flop</h4>\n<p>A sample flip-flop circuit using BC547 transistors, LEDs, resistors and capacitors.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,2,'2026-03-31 19:40:11','2026-03-31 19:40:11',NULL),(15,6,'Printed Circuit Board (PCB) Making','3','<h3>PRINTED CIRCUIT BOARD MAKING</h3>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.5/IMG_20251025_214221.jpg\" alt=\"PCB Making Overview\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>Step 1: Materials</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Copper Clad (2x2)</li>\n<li>Masking Tape</li>\n<li>Ruler</li>\n<li>Knife Cutter</li>\n<li>Pencil</li>\n<li>Mini Drill</li>\n<li>Ferric Chloride</li>\n<li>Sand Paper</li>\n<li>Plastic Container</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h4>Step 2: Designing the circuit</h4>\n<p>Using paper and pencil design the layout of the circuit, it is easiest to do this as a top view of the board. It helps to also have all the different components on hand to help with spacing and placement. As a side note also make sure to design the layout so that it will fit on the board. If you already have a pre-designed layout you can skip this part.</p>\n\n<h4>Step 3: Drawing the traces</h4>\n<p>Next you will want to make a copy of the design that is a reverse of the original, if you drew it in reverse or the one you have is already reversed just make a regular copy of it. Cut the copy of the layout out with scissors leaving some on either side so you can fold it around the PCB and tape it in place. Now using the tape, tape the design onto the copper side of the PCB.</p>\n\n<p>With the #65 drill bit use the layout to drill a hole in the center of all the solder pads for the individual components.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.5/IMG_20251025_214240.jpg\" alt=\"Drawing Traces\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>Step 4: Cutting the Excess</h4>\n<p>Gently glide the knife along the edge of your desired PCB design. Strip the excess masking tape to reveal the design of your work. Try not to puncture the design to prevent damage to the connection that will affect the functionality of your circuit during the etching process.</p>\n\n<h4>Step 5: Etching</h4>\n<p>Start off by finding a clean dry place where you can safely etch the circuit board, preferably outside.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Take your small container and pour about 1/4 to 1/2\" of Ferric Chloride into it.</li>\n<li>Fill the larger container with warm water about 1\" deep.</li>\n<li>Drop PCB into the Ferric Chloride, copper side up and place the small container into the water in the larger container.</li>\n<li>Gently rock the small container in the water so to keep the FC moving which helps with the etching process.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>In about 5-7 minutes you should start to see the copper start to dissolve away, notice the areas where the traces a drawn are unaffected. After about 10-12 minutes the board should be completely etched, at which time you should immediately remove the PCB and drop it into the water in the larger container to rinse it and then dry it off on the paper towel.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.5/IMG_20251025_214303.jpg\" alt=\"Etching Process\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>Step 6: Cleaning the PCB</h4>\n<p>Using 1000 sand paper clean the Sharpie off the traces.</p>\n\n<p><em>Prepare for a Self check and Task Sheet, please provide a sheet of paper as answer sheet.</em></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,3,'2026-03-31 19:40:40','2026-03-31 19:40:40',NULL),(16,7,'What is Soldering and Desoldering?','1','<h3>What is Soldering and Desoldering?</h3>\n\n<p><strong>Soldering</strong> is a process in which two or more metal items are joined together by melting and then flowing a filler metal into the joint—the filler metal having a relatively low melting point. Soldering is used to form a permanent connection between electronic components.</p>\n\n<p>When the strategy involves soldering wire, the work is not about simply welding things together. Aside from simply fusing parts all together, soldering creates electrical contact among components, solidifying their place within the overall circuit board.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Solder</strong> is a fusible metal alloy with a melting point or range of 90 to 450°C (190 to 840°F), used in a process called soldering where it is melted to join metallic surfaces. It is especially useful in electronics and plumbing. Alloys that melt between 180 and 190°C are the most commonly used.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.6/IMG_20251025_214612.jpg\" alt=\"Soldering and Desoldering\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>Soft soldering</h4>\n<p>Soft soldering, which uses a fusible alloy (the filler metal), is characterized by the lower temperatures used and by the higher ductility and (usually) lower strength of the resulting solder joint, as well as a lower value of heat resistance.</p>\n\n<p>Soft soldering can be done with a heated iron tool or in a reflow oven (commonly used for PCB assembly) where heat can be adjusted to melt the solder, commonly lead-based SnPb and lead-free SAC.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2026-03-31 19:49:59','2026-03-31 19:49:59',NULL),(17,7,'Soldering and Desoldering Tools','2','<h3>SOLDERING AND DESOLDERING TOOLS</h3>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.6/IMG_20251025_214638.jpg\" alt=\"Soldering Tools\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>Soldering Iron</h4>\n<p>A soldering iron is what is used to heat the solder. It supplies heat to melt the solder so that it can flow into the joint between two workpieces. A soldering iron is composed of a heated metal tip and an insulated handle.</p>\n\n<h4>Soldering Station</h4>\n<p>A soldering station is a complete unit used for soldering electronic components. It includes the soldering iron and a stand.</p>\n\n<h4>Tweezers (various size)</h4>\n<p>Tweezers are used to pick up and position small components on the PCB. They are also used for removing wire from a printed circuit board (PCB), to remove solder with other means, removing burnt parts or solder wax. It is usually a form or electric or battery powered vacuum that safely suck away any melted solder, flux or other residue from the electronics or circuit board previously soldered.</p>\n\n<h4>Desoldering Pump</h4>\n<p>A desoldering pump is a device used for removing solder from a printed circuit board. It has a trigger mechanism that when pressed releases the solder from the tip of the soldering iron while being held there by pressure, and sucks up the melted solder just like a vacuum or suction.</p>\n\n<h4>A Soldering Gun</h4>\n<p>A soldering gun is an approximately pistol-shaped, electrically powered tool for soldering metals using tin-based solder to achieve a strong mechanical bond with good electrical contact. The tool has a trigger-style switch so it can be easily operated with one hand.</p>\n\n<h4>Heat Gun</h4>\n<p>A heat gun is a tool of heavy equipment with heat generated that helps in removing, repairing, and Servicing by blowing hot air, commonly to shrink or strip components of machinery.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,2,'2026-03-31 19:50:33','2026-03-31 19:50:33',NULL),(18,7,'Soldering Supplies and Materials','3','<h3>SOLDERING SUPPLIES AND MATERIALS</h3>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.6/IMG_20251025_214657.jpg\" alt=\"Soldering Materials\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>Solder</h4>\n<p>Solder is a fusible metal alloy used to create a permanent bond between metal workpieces. Solder is melted in order to wet the metals at the joint. It must contain flux or be used with flux.</p>\n\n<h4>Lead-based Solder (SnPb)</h4>\n<p>Tin/lead solders, also called soft solders, are commercially available with tin concentrations between 5% and 70% by weight. The greater the tin concentration, the greater the solder\'s tensile and shear strengths. The preferred solder for electrical/electronics work is 60/40 Tin/Pb.</p>\n\n<h4>Lead-free Solder (SAC)</h4>\n<p>Due to the toxic effects of lead, the manufacture and use of lead-based solders is being limited. Contact with solder containing lead can be dangerous. SAC (Sn/Ag/Cu) solder, Antimony/Tin/Pb solder have lower melting points from 5 to 20°C higher though molten.</p>\n\n<h4>Flux</h4>\n<p>Flux is a reducing material designed to help reduce (or reverse) metal oxidation, which makes it easier for the solder metal to metallic bond. There are different types of flux using acid flux, flux water, paste type of flux and rosin flux, used in electronics and plumbing, and rosin flux are soldered with either alcohol or acetone to aid in damping delicate circuitry.</p>\n\n<h4>Desoldering Braid/Wick</h4>\n<p>Desoldering braid is a tool for removing solder. It consists of braided 18 to 42 AWG copper wire coated with flux. Desoldering with braid is preferred over other methods because it allows precise control of how much solder to remove.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.6/IMG_20251025_214713.jpg\" alt=\"Solder Types\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,3,'2026-03-31 19:50:33','2026-03-31 19:50:33',NULL),(19,7,'SMD Soldering','4','<h3>SMD SOLDERING</h3>\n\n<p>SMD is the abbreviation of Surface-Mount Device, as the name suggests, it implies that components are mounted on the surface of boards.</p>\n\n<p>SMDs in various configurations are soldered to a Printed Circuit Board (PCB) following a different soldering process than used for through-hole components. Flux is used to process individual SMD components, application of solder paste to the land pads is not required. SMDs can be hand soldered onto PCBs.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.6/IMG_20251025_214726.jpg\" alt=\"SMD Soldering\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>SMD Mounting Configurations</h4>\n<p>Surface Mount Devices (SMD) are available in different configurations:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Passive SMDs (chips)</li>\n<li>Transistors and Diodes</li>\n<li>Integrated Circuits</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Soldering Defects</h4>\n<p>The most common joint defect is melt-through from holding the tip on the joint for too long. A bridge between closely spaced wiring is also common. Another common defect when hand-soldering is the presence of a cold solder joint.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,4,'2026-03-31 19:51:02','2026-03-31 19:51:02',NULL),(20,7,'Identifying Good and Bad Solder Joints','5','<h3>SOLDERING DEFECTS</h3>\n\n<p><strong>\"Cold solder\"</strong> joint resulting from holding the solder directly against the soldering iron instead of letting the parts be heated directly, which then melts the parts being connected for thorough wetting.</p>\n\n<p><strong>A bridge</strong> is a solder joint or crystal head that can cause joint failure, if not carefully made. When it resolves, it may create \"whiskers\" that may short-circuit the joint to electrical mechanically and electrochemically.</p>\n\n<img src=\"/storage/information-sheets/1.6/IMG_20251025_214742.jpg\" alt=\"Good vs Bad Joints\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto; margin: 15px 0;\">\n\n<h4>Good Joint vs Bad Joint</h4>\n<table border=\"1\" style=\"width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;\">\n<tr><th>Good Joint</th><th>Bad Joint</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Shiny and smooth appearance</td><td>Dull or grainy appearance</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Concave fillet shape</td><td>Convex or blob shape</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Complete wetting of surfaces</td><td>Poor wetting or cold joint</td></tr>\n<tr><td>No visible defects</td><td>Cracks, bridges, or voids</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h4>Common Causes of Bad Joints</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>a) Good at soldering:</strong> Smooth and shiny joint</li>\n<li><strong>b) Too much solder:</strong> Excessive solder blob</li>\n<li><strong>c) Poor wetting:</strong> Solder did not flow properly</li>\n<li><strong>d) Fractured, excess flux:</strong> Joint cracked or has residue</li>\n<li><strong>e) Wrong angle:</strong> Lead not properly positioned</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Tips for Good Soldering</h4>\n<p>In electronics, a \"whisper\" (fillet type) is ideal. This indicates good wetting and minimal but complete wetting. Properly hot solder will flow onto a properly fluxed/oiled circuit board trace uniformly, leaving a shiny, hot solder joint profile not being bright and shiny you can not mistake a good solder joint for a bad, frosty bad joint.</p>\n\n<p>PCB may require only heating of the copper land (no pre-tinned). All other parts may already lift off this board, particularly on single-sided PCBs without through-hole plating.</p>\n\n<p><em>Prepare for a Self check and Task Sheet.</em></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,5,'2026-03-31 19:51:02','2026-03-31 19:51:02',NULL);
